Diagnosis.
In the male sex the species can easily be recognised by its long, slender cerci with strong basal tooth.

Head. Fastigium verticis about half as wide as scapus, sulcate at tip, met from below by conical fastigium frontis, leaving a gap between tips. Antennal sockets strongly margined (as typical for Pseudophyllinae ;
Rentz 1979
) (
Fig. 9
D). Scapus large, its distal half slightly inflated. Eyes circular, the diameter at base smaller than further distal.

Wings. Tegmina broader than in male (see
Table 3
). Upper side of right tegmen with nine veins carrying stridulatory teeth.
